Upon the refusal of Achilles to return to the army, the distress of Aga­ memnon is described in the most lively manner.
He takes no rest that night, but passes through the camp, awaking the leaders, and contriving all possible methods for the public safety.
Menelaus, Nestor, Ulysses, and Diomede, are employed in raising the rest of the captains.
They call a council of war, and determine to send scouts into the enemy's camp, to learn their posture, and discover their intentions.
Diomede undertakes this hazardous enterprise, and makes choice of Ulysses for his compa­ nion.
In their passage they surprise Dolon, whom Hector had sent on a like design to the camp of the Grecians.
From him they are inform­ ed of the situation of the Trojan and auxiliary forces, and particularly of Rhesus, and the Thracians, who were lately arrived..
They pass on with succ es;
